com.ibm.lpex.core
Class LpexCommonParser

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--com.ibm.lpex.core.LpexCommonParser
All Implemented Interfaces:
LpexConstants, LpexParser
Direct Known Subclasses:
CobolParser, CppParser, HLAsmParser, HtmlParser, JavaParser, JclParser, PliParser, PropertiesParser, RexxParser, SqlParser, TestParser1, TestParser2, XmlParser, XslParser
public abstract class LpexCommonParser
extends java.lang.Object
implements LpexParser, LpexConstants

LpexCommonParser is an abstract class for document parsers. It adds several services to the regular LpexParser interface, simplifying document-parser development, and provides methods for a common look-and-feel to the parsers extending it. Certain methods in the LpexParser interface are not used by parsers extending LpexCommonParser.

A document parser based on LpexCommonParser will be defined such: 

    public class MyLpexParser extends LpexCommonParser
A parser is associated with one particular view of a document. Different views of the same document may be handled by different parsers. The parser must have a constructor whose parameter is the view of the document. This constructor must first call the constructor of its superclass, LpexCommonParser, as shown below: 
    public MyLpexParser(LpexView lpexView)
    {
       super(lpexView); // this sets LpexCommonParser's protected variable view
       // rest of MyLpexParser's constructor code...
    }
Editor actions modified by parsers extending LpexCommonParser:
  • blockMarkWord to select a token
  • newLine, openLine, splitLine to indent the cursor (current document location) in the new element.

Actions and assigned keys added by LpexCommonParser parsers:

  • match (Ctrl+M) to match parentheses, braces, square brackets, and angle brackets
  • proto (Ctrl+R) to expand templates defined in the parser properties.
Keys already defined (e.g., by the active base profile) to an action different from nullAction are not redefined in here.

getLanguage

public java.lang.String getLanguage()
Retrieve a string identifying the language or file type supported by the parser. This string is used by getProperty() and setProperty() as a prefix to retrieve/set parser properties in LPEX's profile, as a prefix for parser messages in LPEX's resources, and can be used by a command (such as a code navigator) to identify the language handled by the parser.

The document parser extending LpexCommonParser may override this method to return the language it supports. Strings for the most common programming languages are defined in LpexCommonParser. The implementation of this method provided by the LpexCommonParser class returns null.

See Also:

proto

public void proto()
Expand a prototype word at the current document location (cursor) as per the template defined in the active document parser. The cursor is set to the position of the first '?' encountered in the expansion, if any.

The expansion string is obtained through a call to getProperty(), with the prototype word found at the cursor, prefixed by "proto.", as the key argument. If any argument substitution is needed in the expansion string, it should be carried out by the parser extending LpexCommonParser.

When the document is empty, key PROTOKEY_EMPTY is used, if an expansion for it is defined, to allow setting up an initial text to serve as a basic structure for the document.

See Also:
getProperty(java.lang.String), PROTOKEY_EMPTY

getToken

public java.lang.String getToken(LpexDocumentLocation loc)
Get the token at a certain document location. This method can be used for language-sensitive help (LSH).

Returns null if the document location is beyond the element text, is on white space, or loc is incorrect. Token search is restricted to one element. Styles are assumed to be set correctly (i.e., no parse is pending for this element).

A token is a string of a consistent style, and delimited by the boundaries of the text element, white space, and characters defined by isTokenDelimiter().

If a block has been selected and the location (cursor) points to the start or end of this block, then the selected text will be returned as the token. This overrides the normal definition of a token stated above.

Parameters:
loc - document location
See Also:
isTokenDelimiter(char)

matchToken

protected LpexDocumentLocation matchToken(LpexDocumentLocation loc)
Match the token found at a certain document location. A document parser extending LpexCommonParser may override this method to return a matching token to the one found at loc, such as the "end" token matching a "do". This is used by the match action, with loc being the current document location.

If no matching token is returned by this method, LpexCommonParser tries to match any parenthesis, brace, square bracket, or angle bracket found at loc. A successful match will result in the character-selection of the text bounded by the two tokens.

The implementation of this method provided by the LpexCommonParser class does nothing, except return null.

Parameters:
loc - document location

isTokenDelimiter

public boolean isTokenDelimiter(char ch)
Returns true if the specified character is a token delimiter. While a punctuation character, for example, will have a style different from the token adjacent to it, this method is used to identify one token inside a string of tokens of the same style which may appear in the source without any other separators: e.g., 
   ... (name());
in a Java-language source.

The implementation of this method provided by the LpexCommonParser class returns false. The parser should override this to return its particular token delimiters.

See Also:
getToken(com.ibm.lpex.core.LpexDocumentLocation)

cursorIndent

public int cursorIndent(int element)
Get the indent display column of the cursor in the element. LpexCommonParser redefines the editor actions newLine and openLine, which are the default actions of Shift+Enter and Ctrl+Enter. In newLine, after the cursor was moved to the next visible element in the view, if any, this method is called to set its optimal column. In openLine, the cursor on the new empty element is positioned on the column returned by this method.

The implementation of this method provided by the LpexCommonParser class returns the display column of the beginning of text in this element, if any, or otherwise the column corresponding to the beginning of text in the preceding non-blank element, if any, or otherwise column 1; 1 is also returned if automatic indentation is disabled. Show elements are ignored.

A document parser may override this method, to return a value appropriate to its auto-indentation scheme.

Parameters:
element - the element for cursor indentation
Returns:
optimal display cursor column
See Also:
setAutoIndent(boolean)

textIndent

public int textIndent(int element)
Get the indent display column for text in the element. LpexCommonParser redefines the action splitLine, which is the default action of the Enter key. In splitLine, after a new element was created for the split text, this method is called to obtain the optimal column for positioning its text and cursor; if the new element is empty, cursorIndent() is called instead, to just position the cursor.

The implementation of this method provided by the LpexCommonParser class returns the display column corresponding to the beginning of text in the preceding non-blank element, if any, or otherwise column 1; 1 is also returned if automatic indentation is disabled. Show elements are ignored.

A document parser may override this method, to return a value appropriate to its auto-indentation scheme.

Parameters:
element - the element for text indentation
Returns:
optimal display column for text and cursor
See Also:
setAutoIndent(boolean)

protected void splitLine()
Overrides the default editor action splitLine. It positions the text and the cursor (current document location) in the new element to the display column returned by textIndent().

An incremental parse is triggered in here to ensure text tokenization is current.

addMessage

public final void addMessage(int element,
                             java.lang.String text)
Display a parser error or informational message for an element. No imbedded messages are displayed if this feature is disabled. Parser error messages are assigned the CLASS_MESSAGE element class, and are set the STYLE_MESSAGE style character.

The messages to be inserted during a parse action are stacked. The actual insertion of the show-line messages will be carried out at the end of the current parse action. Several messages for one line will be displayed in the order they were added.

It is recommended that the text of the message be obtained from a locale-sensitive resource.

Parameters:
element - the element number this message pertains to
text - the message text
See Also:
setErrorMessages(boolean), removeMessages(int, int), CLASS_MESSAGE, STYLE_MESSAGE

removeMessages

public final void removeMessages(int fromElement,
                                 int toElement)
Remove this parser's error messages for a given range of elements.

The actual removal of embedded error messages will be carried out at the end of the current parse action. Calls to this method during the course of one parse action may extend a range already set. Note that the range is assumed to be continuous.

Parameters:
fromElement - first text element in the range
toElement - last text element for which this parser's messages should be removed
See Also:
addMessage(int, java.lang.String)
